        <div class="eyebrow">Chapter III</div>
        <h1>Rhythm &amp; Meter</h1>
        <p class="kicker">How sound is organized in time — pulse, time signatures, syncopation, and the rhythmic character of different genres.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>Defining Rhythm and Meter</h2>
      <p><strong>Rhythm</strong> refers to the arrangement of sounds and silences in time — the pattern of long and short notes, or the duration of musical events. <strong>Meter</strong> is the organization of beats into regular groupings; it gives music its sense of pulse and is typically indicated by a time signature.</p>

      <h3>Counting Note Values</h3>
      <p>The basic rhythmic values in Western music notation are whole, half, quarter, eighth, and sixteenth notes. Here is how each is counted within the most common meter, 4/4.</p>
      <dl class="deflist">
        <dt>Whole Note (Semibreve)</dt>
        <dd>Four beats in 4/4. One per measure — counted "1, 2, 3, 4" or held for the entire measure.</dd>

        <dt>Half Note (Minim)</dt>
        <dd>Two beats in 4/4. Counted "1, 2" or held for the first two beats of the measure.</dd>

        <dt>Quarter Note (Crotchet)</dt>
        <dd>One beat in 4/4. Counted "1, 2, 3, 4" — each number a beat.</dd>

        <dt>Eighth Note (Quaver)</dt>
        <dd>Half a beat in 4/4. Counted "1 &amp; 2 &amp; 3 &amp; 4 &amp;" — the "&amp;" is the second half of each beat.</dd>

        <dt>Sixteenth Note (Semiquaver)</dt>
        <dd>Quarter of a beat in 4/4. Counted "1 e &amp; a, 2 e &amp; a, 3 e &amp; a, 4 e &amp; a" — each syllable a subdivision.</dd>
      </dl>

      <h3>Counting in Other Meters</h3>
      <p>In meters other than 4/4, the counting changes but the basic note values stay the same.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>In <strong>3/4</strong> (waltz time), the count is "1, 2, 3" per measure, with a quarter note receiving one beat.</li>
        <li>In <strong>6/8</strong> (compound duple meter), each measure typically contains two beats, each subdivided into three eighth notes — so "1 &amp; a, 2 &amp; a" per measure.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Time Signatures</h2>
      <p>Time signatures indicate meter in music notation. They specify the number of beats per measure and the type of note that receives one beat. The top and bottom numbers each have specific meanings:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Top number</strong> — the number of beats per measure. In 4/4, four beats per measure.</li>
        <li><strong>Bottom number</strong> — the type of note that gets one beat, expressed as a fraction of a whole note. A <em>4</em> on the bottom means a quarter note gets one beat; an <em>8</em> means an eighth note does.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Examples</h3>
      <dl class="deflist">
        <dt>4/4 — Common Time</dt>
        <dd>Four beats per measure, quarter note gets one beat. The most common time signature in Western music.</dd>

        <dt>3/4 — Waltz Time</dt>
        <dd>Three beats per measure, quarter note gets one beat. Associated with waltzes.</dd>

        <dt>6/8 — Compound Duple Meter</dt>
        <dd>Six eighth notes per measure, eighth note gets one beat. Common in marches and lively music.</dd>
      </dl>

      <figure class="diagram-figure">
        <svg viewBox="0 0 600 140" class="staff-svg" role="img" aria-label="One measure each in 4/4, 3/4, and 6/8 time, written on a staff.">
