      <h2>Syncopation</h2>
      <p>Syncopation is a rhythmic technique where emphasis is placed on off-beats or weak beats within a phrase, creating tension and anticipation. Instead of accenting strong beats (typically 1 and 3 in 4/4), syncopated rhythms accent weak beats or the spaces between beats. This is achieved through tied notes, rests, and accents on upbeats.</p>

      <h3>What syncopation does for the music</h3>
      <dl class="deflist">
        <dt>Creates groove and momentum</dt>
        <dd>Accents on unexpected beats make the music feel dynamic and energetic — it makes listeners want to move.</dd>

        <dt>Adds tension and interest</dt>
        <dd>Disrupting the regular pattern adds excitement and intrigue, keeping the listener engaged.</dd>

        <dt>Enhances musical texture</dt>
        <dd>Layers complexity that contrasts with straightforward rhythms, making the music richer.</dd>

        <dt>Expresses musical style</dt>
        <dd>Common in jazz, funk, Latin, and rock — it helps define the characteristic feel of those genres.</dd>
      </dl>

      <h3>Syncopated standards</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>"Superstition"</strong> — Stevie Wonder. The guitar riff and drum pattern are deeply syncopated.</li>
        <li><strong>"Take Five"</strong> — Dave Brubeck. Famous for its 5/4 meter and syncopated melody.</li>
        <li><strong>"I Got Rhythm"</strong> — George Gershwin. Syncopation throughout melody and accompaniment.</li>
        <li><strong>"Billie Jean"</strong> — Michael Jackson. The bassline accents off-beats; iconic and danceable.</li>
        <li><strong>"Smooth"</strong> — Santana ft. Rob Thomas. Latin-infused syncopation in guitar and percussion.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Meter by Genre</h2>
      <p>Meter — the organization of beats into regular groupings — varies significantly across genres, contributing to the distinct rhythmic feel of each style.</p>

      <h3>Classical Music</h3>
      <p>Classical music often uses meters such as 3/4 (waltz), 4/4 (common), and 2/4 (duple), among others. Composers typically use symmetrical meters where each measure divides into equal parts. Modern compositions and folk-influenced pieces may use irregular meters such as 5/4 or 7/8.</p>

      <h3>Jazz</h3>
      <p>Jazz features complex and flexible meters with frequent syncopation and swing feel. Common meters include 4/4, 3/4, and 6/8, but jazz musicians frequently play with subdivisions and accents, creating polyrhythms and cross-rhythms. Odd meters like 5/4, 7/4, or 11/8 add to the rhythmic interest and improvisational character.</p>

      <h3>Rock Music</h3>
      <p>Rock typically uses simple meters such as 4/4 or 2/4 (cut time), emphasizing a strong backbeat on beats 2 and 4. The rhythm section provides a driving groove and steady pulse. Some bands incorporate irregular meters into compositions for added interest, especially in progressive or avant-garde rock.</p>

      <h3>Comparison</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Classical</strong> — adheres to traditional meters, focused on formal structure and clarity.</li>
        <li><strong>Jazz</strong> — rhythmically adventurous; emphasizes improvisation, syncopation, swing, and complex meters.</li>
        <li><strong>Rock</strong> — steady, driving rhythm, usually 4/4; focused on groove and energy.</li>
      </ul>

